{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_jacobs_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684265/1908051501/0611.xml":{"full_text":"Commission Ready to\nBuild Woman\u2019s College\nMontgomery Has Done\nHer Part*\nCOMMISSION DIRECTS\nBIDS TO BE ASKED FOR\nMain Building and One Dormitory\nOrdered.\nArchitect* WU1 at Oaec Work Oat the\nPlane\u2014 Some of the Feed* Aaaeea\ned Against the two Conference*\nAre Yet to Be Collected.\nThe City of Montgomery has done Its\npart and the work Is soon to begin\non the Methodist Woman's College\nBids will be advertised for at once\nand the preliminary steps will be\ntaken toward* the erection of the In\nstitution which will mean so much to\nthe Methodists of Alabama and to the\npeople of Montgomery.\nThe first building to be erected\nwill be the main building and one or\nthe dormitories.\nThe Building Commission at a recent\nmeeting In Montgomery surveyed tne\nfield and decided to go ahead with tne\nwork. The Commission has preceded\ncautiously and conaervatlvely. Tne\nCommission has been sure of Its\nground before each advance. The or\niginal Intention of the Commtaalon\nv.-aa to begin the actual work on tne\nhulldlnga last fall. Thta was postponed\nbecause of the financial panic. Jn tne\npanic there was necessarily some delay\nIn the collection of the promised sub\nscriptions.\nThe City of Montgomery had pledg\ned |S0 000 In cash to the college in\naddition to the splendid pile of twen\nty-eight acres situated in a command\ning hill on the Woodley road, three\nmiles from tho city. The greater part\nof this amount had been collected last\nfall. The local committee after tne\noverwhelming financial panic had some\ndifficulty In collecting In cash the n\nnal 15.000. This had been secured In\nfirst-class negotiable paper and at the\nbuilding meeting of the Building Com\nmission. Captain A. G. Forbes, Pres\nident of the Montgomery Commercial\nClub presented a report showing that\nthe money promised by the city was\nIn hand with the exception of a small\npart which waa In paper that would be\nhandled by the banka when It was\nneeded.\nIt will be recalled that the Methodists\nwho led In the movement for the col\nCASTOR IA\nFor Infanta and Children.\nThe Kind Yon Hava Always Bought\nBears the\nSignature of\nlegs decided that 160.00# ehould he\nsubscribed by the two Alabama con\nferences. This was to be subscribed\nto meet the generous offer of the heirs\nof John J. Flowers. who offered 160,\n000 provided a like sura should be sub\nscribed by the two Alabama Confer\nences. Rev. J. M. Dannelly. the fin\nancial agent of the college reported to\nthe Coneferenee Commission that\nthe two conferences had pledged about\n140,000 of the amount In the face ot\nthe recent financial panic. He was quite\nsura that the ether would be subscrib\ned and he saw a large part of it al\nready In sight.\nIt was noted that the conditions of\nthe gift of the Flowers heirs were\npositive and exact. The money must\nbe subscribed by the two Conferences\nby next fell.\nOn hearing of the report of the fin\nancial conditions of the College Fund.\nRev. A. J. Lamar and Judge W. H.\nThomas offered a resolution declaring\nthat the Building Committee should be\nauthorized to ask for and receive bids\nfor the construction of the main build\ning and one dormitory, according to\nthe plans of the architect. It was\nfurther provided that separate bids for\neach of the windings should S>e asked\nfor.\nThis resolution was adopted unan\nimously by the Commission.\nThe bids will not be asked for at\nonce. It is plainly stated that the ar\nchitect should prepare the plans and\nspecifications and until this Is done tne\nbids can not be asked for.\nThe Commission was further In\nstructed to confer with Mess. Sellers.\nZlrkle and Moore with reference to\nlaying out and planning the grounds.\nThe business of this conference will\nbe to lay out the walks and grounds\non the handsome college property.\nThe details of the two handsome\nbuildings which are to be erected In\nthe near future will be announced as\nsoon as they are werked out by the\narchitect. They will be as handsome\nand as substantial as money can make\nthem for the promoters of the college\nare building it for all time.\nThe set policy adopted by the col\nlege la that It shall be of the highest\ngrade of Southern Institutions. The\nbuildings will be erected with the\nview that the Institution Is to occupy\na front rank In the educational insti\ntutions of the South.\nThe establishment of the college Is\nan Incident In the history of Montgom\nery In which all people of the city\ntake vital Interest. The whole city\nwill labor for the success of the In\neltuatlon. It fills, too. a singular over\nsight In the life and history of Mont\ngomery. The city has never been an\neducational center. Why this should\nbe It has never been satisfactorily ex\nplained, for by location, environment\nand aspirations. Montgomery le an\nIdeal location for a college. The city,\ntherefore, takes a vital personal Inter\nest In the Methodist College and Its\nwelfare.\nNegro Kills Uegre.\nGreenville, May 14.\u2014(Special)\u2014A ne\ngro was killed by another negro on\nthe plantation of J. R. White several\nmiles from town They were working\ntogether In a field, and the trouble be\ngan by the murdered negro teasing\nthe other. This angered him. and pro\ncuring a gun he began firing, the third\nshot killing him. The murderer was\ncaptured that night In Crenshaw conn\nty by Sheriff Wat ion who \u00bbu accom\npanied by Deputy Sheriff Murphy and\nH. Shonki, and le now In Jail.\neradication or mosruito.\nSlek Rate at Amy rorta la Greatly\nWashington. May II.\u2014Careful at\ntention to the eradication of the mos\nquito and the destruction of Its breed\ning places, a thorough screening of\nthe buildings and the use of quinine by\narmy surgeons at Forts Hunt and\nWashington, on the Potomac River dur\ning the year, has resulted In a vivid\nreduction of the sick rate.\nLast year those posts were distin\nguished by having the highest malarial\nrate In military posts In the United\nStates, but through the e:orts of ths\nmedical officers the sick rate from ma\nlarial fever at Fort Washington haa\nbeen reduced to leas than one-half oi\nthe preceding year, while the reduc\ntion at Fart Hunt haa been reduced\nto about ode-third.\nPRISON WARDEN LOST\nHIS FAT POCKETBOOK\nJailer Pettua Found It and Mr. Bird\nCheered Up.\nIt was not because he had suffered a\nsunstroke that H. D. Bird, deputy war\nden at. Pratt mlnee, (trolled so list\nlessly ihto the County Jail yeeterday\nafternoon. Mr. Bird was making a\nweary search. not for an escaped con\nvict, but for an escaped pocketbook,\nand he was tired. If he ever got his\nhaAda on that receptacle of weultn\nagain, waa his unexpressed feeling, he\nwould handcuff lt\u201e If such a proceed\ning were necessary to restrain Its\nflighty Impulses. It was a nice pock\u2018\netbook, but the grief of Mr. Bird was\noccasioned by the fact that, when In\nthe manner of him that hath he last\ncontentedly viewed the contents, l\u00ab7\nlay snugly within the Inside flap.\nAlmost hopelessly he naraated to\nJailer Pettua the events leading up t\nths tlmA when he flrst missed his be\nlonging. He was ready to play tnt\npart of the father to the prodigal son.\nIn the person of the strayed book, that\nsympathy exuded spontaneously from\nthe visages of all of those who listen\ned to his tale.\nFlnalty, when gloom, deep and sil\nent. had oast Its shadow upon the of\nfice, Jalfcr Pettus with nothing of the\nair of the- philanthropist and in seem\ning WtAoeehcS carelessly produced from\nhis safe a black leather pocketbook.\nI which appeared fat and full of some\nthing. If not gulls.\nMr. Bird awakened from the sorow\nful repose tn which he waa Indulging\ni when he realized the full significance\nof this Incident. Keeptng his eyes upon\nthe article Just produced, he eagerly\nbegun a description of the article he\nhad lost. He stated the amount whlen\nhad been In the book, and without any\nquestioning ho broadly delineated the\ncharacter of the bills which had com\nposed the total of which fate or for\ntune had deprived him.\nJailer Pettus handed him the book,\nand light glowed In the ofllee. It de\nveloped that Mr. Bird had left the book\nat the Jail after an early morning visit\nand that Jailer Pettus had known all\nalong where ths missing property of\nMr. Bird could be found. But as Mr.\nBird Is In the habit of losing some\nthing every time he visits Montgom\nery. Jailer Pettua thought that he\nwould lmpreaa upon him by the sear\ning effect of anxiety, perhaps a lettls\nneedlessly prolonged, the folly of leav\ning something snywhere, or anything\n\"somewhere.\" But Mr. Bird did not\nmind, and everything ended happily.\nBANKERS GATHERING\nBTATB ASSOCIATION Win, CON.\nVENE HERE THIS MORNING.\nNotable Gathering FlMwirri of\nAlabama to Dlecuea Ruitlart,\nHatter*\u2014William B. nMarly\nWUI link Today.\nThe banker* of Alabama will gather\nIn Montgomery today and hear their\nown and other*' counsel a* to the best\nmethod* of handling other people'*\nmoney. The first session win he held\nI. J. Back. Pmlifit at State Aaea*\n\u2022tatloa.\nIn the Majestic Theatre at 10 o\u2019clock\nIn order that sufficient accommodation\nmay be provided for those who wish\nto hear the principal speaker of the\nconvention. William B. Ridgely. for\nMeLaae Tilton. Secretary-Treasurer.\nmarly Comptroller of the United States\nTreasury, and now president of a\nprominent bank In Kansas City. Mo.\nThe addresses of welcome will be\ndelivered by C. F. Morlt*. chairman\nof Finance Committee of the Council,\non behalf of the city, and by Robert\nF. Ucon, on behalf of the Montgom\nery Clearing Houae Ranke. The re\nsponse for the association will be made\nby John H. Frye, of Birmingham.\nIn addition to the addresses there\nwill be the transaction of routine\nbusiness today. Inclusive of the ap\npointment and the reports of group\nofficers and committees.\nIn the afternoon addresses will be\nmade by Alfred J. McGrath, of Phil\nadelphia, George E. Allen, of New\nYork, and S. D. Bcudder, of New\nYork. In the evening session of the\nfirst day Sol Wexler. of New Orleans.\nWalter D. Seed, of Alabama, and Tom\nO. Smith, of Birmingham, will speak.\nThat the attendance upon this ses\nsion will be the largest In the history\nof the association Is already assured.\nThe bankers of Alabama who have\nWilliam RMfrir< Ex-Caaptnlln of\nTram;.\nalready arrived are of themselves a\nnotable number, and many more are\nexpected.\nThe reception of visiting financier*\nby the local entertainment committee\nof the aaaoclatlon vai a pleasant fea\nture of the annual coming together.\nMobil*. May 14\u2014 (Special)\u2014Among\nthe delegate* to tha Alabama Bankaro\nAssociation In Montgomery, tomorrow\nwill be th* following rapreaentatlvao\nof th* Mobil* banka: Charles D Wil\nloughby, Alfred Preakauer, J. W. Little,\nSidney Lowcn\u00bbteln. and B. J. Buck.\nIt aeeaia t* he la th* ala, that Mar\ngaa 9. Gilmer will he ear next Taa\nAnnnr, *0 let all ef a* pall together\nand make It aaaalmeo*.\nMOT IN OATTOB.\nRepabHeeas *ad Polleemea Hare Plght\nla Theatre.\nDayton. May 14.\u2014A riot over the\npoaseaalon of the half of the Republi\ncan Congretalona! Convention occurred\nat Eaton ahortly after midnight. In\nwhich fourteen policemen were roughly\nhandled by armed m*n of the \"Bteaer\"\nfaction.\nA week ago Oscar A Gale, chair,\nman of th* Congressional Committee,\narranged with Mayor Miller for ths\nuse of tha opera house In which to\nbold the convention today. yesterday\nan adherent of the Bleser faction call,\ned and conveying the Impression that\nhe came from Oialrman Gale, tendered\npayment for the opera house, which\nwas accepted and a receipt given. The\nHarding faction fearing a move to ex.\nelude Its delegatee from the opera\nhouse during the session of the con*\nventlon had stationed special police\nmen In the hall, who were assaulted